{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619727"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:35:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:35:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16572"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16572"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.09,0.14,0.68,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9263"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75563"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9263"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16572"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61080"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1675"},{"type":"tags","id":"2779"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"9872"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21943"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21947"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75563"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EParkinson\u0027s disease is a neurological disease with both motor and non-motor symptoms and signs. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following non-motor complications of Parkinson\u0027s disease is most appropriately treated with fludrocortisone or midodrine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hallucinations","Depression","Constipation","Postural hypotension","Impulse control disorder"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOrthostatic or \u003Cstrong\u003Epostural hypotension\u003C/strong\u003E is a common non-motor complication of Parkinson\u0027s disease. \u003Cstrong\u003EPostural hypotension\u003C/strong\u003E can be treated with fludrocortisone (a mineralocorticoid that increases sodium retention and by consequence blood volume) or midodrine (an alpha-1 agonist that causes vasoconstriction). Other non-pharmacological measures include increasing fluid and salt intake, wearing compression stockings, and avoiding sudden position changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese medications would not be therapeutic for any of the other non-motor features of Parkinson\u0027s disease listed in this question.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHallucinations\u003C/strong\u003E can be either a consequence of medications used for Parkinson\u0027s disease, or a feature of the disease itself. They can be managed by modifying existing treatments or with the cautious addition of an atypical neuroleptic e.g. quetiapine or clozoine. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDepression\u003C/strong\u003E in Parkinson\u0027s disease is typically treated with selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) or cognitive behavioural therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConstipation\u003C/strong\u003E is managed with dietary modification, increased fluid intake, and osmotic laxatives such as macrogol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpulse control disorders\u003C/strong\u003E are managed by reducing or withdrawing dopamine agonists and providing psychological support.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-motor symptoms of Parkinson\u0027s disease can significantly impact quality of life and often require specific management strategies distinct from those used for motor symptoms. The choice of treatment depends on the specific symptom and should consider potential interactions with other medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Postural hypotension is a common non-motor complication of Parkinson\u0027s disease that can be treated with fludrocortisone or midodrine.","Non-motor symptoms of Parkinson\u0027s disease often have a greater impact on quality of life than motor symptoms.","Fludrocortisone acts by increasing sodium retention while midodrine is a vasoconstrictor."],"references":["Fanciulli A, Leys F, Falup-Pecurariu C, Thijs R, Wenning GK. Management of Orthostatic Hypotension in Parkinson\u0027s Disease. J Parkinsons Dis. 2020;10(s1):S57-S64. doi: 10.3233/JPD-202036. PMID: 32716319; PMCID: PMC7592655.","Kobylecki C. Update on the diagnosis and management of Parkinson\u0027s disease. Clin Med (Lond). 2020 Jul;20(4):393-398. doi: 10.7861/clinmed.2020-0220. PMID: 32675145; PMCID: PMC7385761","Armstrong MJ, Okun MS. Diagnosis and Treatment of Parkinson Disease: A Review. JAMA. 2020 Feb 11;323(6):548-560. doi: 10.1001/jama.2019.22360. PMID: 32044947"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61080"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16572"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61080"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T11:00:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T11:02:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9263"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75563"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"desc